1184	+//! SCHED scheduling policy + per-proc state table (slice 4.3).
1185	+//!
1186	+//! SCHED is minix.rs's user-space scheduler. The kernel run queue is
1187	+//! *delegatable*: when a SCHED-scheduled proc exhausts its quantum the kernel
1188	+//! sends `SCHEDULING_NO_QUANTUM`, and SCHED re-admits the proc via
1189	+//! `SYS_SCHEDULE`, choosing its priority band and quantum. This module holds the
1190	+//! per-proc policy state — a fixed `[SchedProc; CAP]` table wrapped in an
1191	+//! `UnsafeCell` newtype, exactly like the DS registry and the VM region table —
1192	+//! plus the pure policy helpers; the IPC/kernel-call glue lives in `main.rs`.
1193	+//!
1194	+//! **Policy (4.3): round-robin quantum refresh at a fixed managed band**
1195	+//! ([`USER_Q`]). Each `SCHEDULING_NO_QUANTUM` re-admits the proc at its recorded
1196	+//! priority with a fresh quantum. The managed band equals the boot servers' band
1197	+//! (`SRV_Q = 8`) so a CPU-bound managed proc round-robins with the
1198	+//! kernel-scheduled procs instead of sinking behind them. MINIX's priority aging
1199	+//! (drop a band on full-quantum use, periodically re-raised by `balance_queues`)
1200	+//! needs the per-proc alarm from `SYS_SETALARM` (slice 4.4): without the
1201	+//! compensating boost, dropping a band would starve the managed proc behind the
1202	+//! kernel-scheduled band-8 stubs, so it is deferred.
1203	+//!
1204	+//! The pure `*_in` helpers operate on a borrowed array and carry the host unit
1205	+//! tests; the thin `schedule_proc`/`record`/`forget` wrappers reach the static
1206	+//! and are the only `unsafe` here — the same split as the DS registry.
1207	+
1208	+use core::cell::UnsafeCell;
1209	+
1210	+/// Managed priority band. Matches the kernel's `SRV_Q` so a CPU-bound managed
1211	+/// proc round-robins with the kernel-scheduled boot procs / stubs rather than
1212	+/// sinking behind them (see the module note on deferred priority aging).
1213	+pub const USER_Q: u8 = 8;
1214	+
1215	+/// Quantum (kernel ticks) SCHED hands out. Small so a CPU-bound proc exhausts it
1216	+/// often, making the delegation round-trip visible in the boot trace.
1217	+pub const QUANTUM: i32 = 5;
1218	+
1219	+/// Per-proc policy-state table capacity. Covers every boot proc plus the stubs;
1220	+/// no allocator, so this is a hard cap (a new proc past it is simply left
1221	+/// unmanaged — it stays blocked, the user-space equivalent of "can't schedule").
1222	+const CAP: usize = 16;
1223	+
1224	+/// One managed proc's scheduling state. `in_use == false` marks a free slot.
1225	+#[derive(Copy, Clone)]
1226	+struct SchedProc {
1227	+    proc_nr: i32,
1228	+    priority: u8,
1229	+    quantum: i32,
1230	+    in_use: bool,
1231	+}
1232	+
1233	+impl SchedProc {
1234	+    const EMPTY: Self = Self {
1235	+        proc_nr: 0,
1236	+        priority: 0,
1237	+        quantum: 0,
1238	+        in_use: false,
1239	+    };
1240	+}
